To save data to local storage in JavaScript, use the `localStorage.setItem()` method and to retrieve data, use the `localStorage.getItem()` method.

Here's an example:

```javascript
// Save data to local storage
localStorage.setItem('name', 'John Doe');

// Retrieve data from local storage
let name = localStorage.getItem('name');
console.log(name);

// Update existing data in local storage
localStorage.setItem('age', 25);

// Delete data from local storage
localStorage.removeItem('age');
```

In this example, we're saving a name and age to local storage using the `setItem()` method. Then we retrieve the name and log it to the console. We also update an existing item (age) and delete another one (also called age).

Note: The key-value pairs in local storage are stored as strings, so if you're storing a number or object, make sure to convert it to a string before saving it and back to its original form when retrieving it.
